.\" This man page is generated from xboing.man.in by CMake; @PROJECT_VERSION@
.\" and @MAN_DATE@ are substituted from project(VERSION) and XBOING_MAN_DATE.
.\"
.TH XBOING 6 "@MAN_DATE@" "xboing @PROJECT_VERSION@" "Games Manual"
.SH NAME
xboing \- classic breakout/blockout arcade game (SDL2)
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B xboing
.RI [ options ]
.RS 4
.nf
-speed <1-9>        Game speed (1=slowest, 9=fastest, default 5)
-startlevel <1-80>  Start at the given level (default 1)
-keys               Use keyboard control (default: mouse)
-nickname <name>    Set high-score nickname
-debug              Enable debug mode
-grab               Confine the mouse pointer to the window
-load               On startup, load the saved game (skips the attract cycle)
-sound              Enable sound (default)
-nosound            Disable all audio
-nosfx              Disable visual special effects (screen shake, etc.)
-maxvol <0-100>     Maximum volume percentage (default 80)
-help, -usage       Show the option summary and exit
-version            Show the version and exit
-setup              Show the resolved configuration paths and exit
-scores             Show high scores (personal, plus global) and exit
.fi
.RE
.SH DESCRIPTION
XBoing is a blockout game: you control a paddle at the bottom of the arena
and bounce a proton ball to destroy the blocks above without letting the
ball fall past the paddle.
.PP
Each block carries a different point value; the more you destroy, the
higher your score. The arena is filled with blocks and special objects,
and the paddle moves left and right along the bottom much like pinball.
.PP
This is a faithful SDL2 modernization of the original 1993-1997 X11 game by
Justin C. Kibell. All 80 levels, the ball physics, the 30+ block types,
power-ups, multiball, and the built-in level editor are preserved.
Project home: https://github.com/jmf-pobox/xboing-c
.SH BLOCK TYPES
The blocks exhibit different behaviour. The bomb block when hit explodes
all blocks around it (you score the points for the blocks it destroys); an
adjacent bomb chains. The solid wall brick will not explode unless next to
a bomb. The ammunition block gives you four bullets; an unlimited-ammo
block grants endless bullets for that level.
.PP
Random blocks change colour, and therefore points, periodically. A pirate
(death) symbol kills your ball if touched \(em shoot it three times to
destroy it. The walls-off block lets the ball pass through the left and
right walls and wrap to the opposite side. The extra-time block adds 20
seconds to the level clock.
.PP
The reverse block reverses the paddle controls (hit another to cancel;
reset each ball). The teleport block moves the ball elsewhere on the level.
The sticky-paddle block catches the ball until you fire. Some blocks drop
down the screen (their score decreases as they fall). A roaming dude wanders
the arena and is worth a few hundred points. The machine-gun block lets you
shoot much faster (using bullets faster too).
.PP
Extra-ball, shrink-paddle and grow-paddle symbols affect the paddle/ball
when hit. Bonus coins appear throughout play and are awarded when the level
completes; x2/x4 coins multiply scoring until the next ball death. A little
eye dude occasionally walks across the top row (if clear) and is worth
10000 points if hit. Collect more than 10 bonuses in a level to trigger
killer mode \(em the ball turns red and ploughs through all non-solid
blocks.
.PP
The bonus screen tallies the level: 500 points per unused bullet, 3000 per
bonus coin, a 50000-point SUPER BONUS for more than 8 bonuses, and an extra
ball every 100000 points. Press Space to skip the bonus animation (points
still count). A level timer counts down; finishing in time awards 100
points per second remaining. The ball auto-launches after about five
seconds unless you press Space, and the board auto-tilts if the ball loops
without hitting the paddle.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI -speed " <1-9>"
Game speed, 1 (slowest) to 9 (fastest). Default 5. Also changeable in-game
with the number keys.
.TP
.BI -startlevel " <1-80>"
Start at the given level. Default 1. Note that the high-score "level" is
the number of levels completed, not the level reached.
.TP
.B -keys
Use the keyboard for paddle control instead of the mouse. Default: mouse.
.TP
.BI -nickname " <name>"
Use the given nickname in the high-score table instead of your account
name (max 20 characters).
.TP
.B -debug
Enable debug mode.
.TP
.B -grab
Confine the mouse pointer to the game window.
.TP
.B -load
On startup, load the previously saved game and skip the attract cycle.
.TP
.B -sound
Enable audio. This is the default.
.TP
.B -nosound
Disable all audio (music and sound effects).
.TP
.B -nosfx
Disable the visual special effects (screen shake, fade, blind, etc.).
Audio is controlled separately by
.BR -sound / -nosound .
.TP
.BI -maxvol " <0-100>"
Maximum volume as a percentage (default 80); other sounds scale against
this ceiling. A value of 0 is ignored: it neither overrides the configured
volume nor mutes audio. Use
.B -nosound
to silence audio.
.TP
.B -help ", " -usage
Print the option summary and exit.
.TP
.B -version
Print the version and exit.
.TP
.B -setup
Print the resolved level, sound, and score paths and exit. Useful for
diagnosing an installation.
.TP
.B -scores
Print high scores to standard output and exit: your personal table always,
and the global ("roll of honour") table where one exists (the Debian setgid
install, or when XBOING_SCORE_FILE is set).
.SH GAME CONTROL
Move the paddle with the mouse; any mouse button launches the ball and
fires bullets. Press
.B g
to switch between mouse and keyboard control (or start with
.BR -keys ).
.PP
During a game:
.RS 4
.nf
Space    Launch the ball       K        Shoot bullet
Left, J  Paddle left           Right, L Paddle right
p        Pause / resume        t        Tilt the board
d        Kill the current ball
z        Save the game         x        Load the saved game
Escape   Abort the current game
.fi
.RE
.PP
At the intro / attract screens:
.RS 4
.nf
h        Global high scores (roll of honour)
Shift+H  Personal high scores
s        Toggle visual special effects
w        Set the starting level
c        Cycle the attract screens
1-9      Set game speed (9 = fastest)
.fi
.RE
.PP
Any time:
.RS 4
.nf
a        Toggle audio on/off
+ / -    Raise / lower the maximum volume
i        Toggle fullscreen
g        Switch mouse / keyboard control
e        Open the level editor (from a game or the attract screens)
q        Quit
.fi
.RE
.SH SAVE/LOAD GAME
XBoing supports a one-slot save. Every five completed levels you may save
once; the ability to save is indicated by a highlighted "Save" in the
specials area below the arena. Press the save key to write the saved game
(overwriting any previous save). Press the load key during a normal game to
resume from the save.
.PP
The saved game is stored under your data directory (see FILES). On load the
ball resumes mid-flight from the saved position.
.SH LEVEL EDITOR
Press
.B e
\(em from the intro/attract screens or during a game \(em to open the
built-in level editor. Click a
block type in the tool bar, then draw into the level: the left mouse button
draws, Shift+left-click erases, and the right button reports a block's
point value. Hold and drag while drawing or erasing for continuous action;
the right button is a single-click inspect. The middle button also erases,
for mice with a third button; most trackpads and
two-button mice don't have one, so Shift+left-click is the portable
binding. You can play-test the level (infinite lives, never ends) and flip
or scroll the board. Editor keys:
.RS 4
.nf
q  Exit editor
p  Start/end play test
r  Redraw the level
s  Save the level
l  Load the level
c  Clear the level
t  Change the time bonus
n  Change the level name
v  Flip vertically       V  Scroll one block vertically
h  Flip horizontally     H  Scroll one block horizontally
.fi
.RE
.SH SCORING
Each block has a point value; some (such as the counter block) carry
several. Hitting the paddle with the ball earns 10 points. Completing level
.I n
in time awards a level bonus of
.IR n " x 100"
points. Representative block values:
.RS 4
.nf
red    100      blue    110     green   120
yellow 140      tan     130     purple  150
bomb    50      wall      0     roamer  400
drop  row x 100 specials 100    ammo   50 + bullets
counter 200 (per number)
.fi
.RE
.SH HIGH SCORES
XBoing keeps a per-user
.B personal
high-score table on every platform, under your data directory (see FILES).
.PP
A shared, cross-user
.B global
high-score table (the "roll of honour", with per-user de-duplication and
the Boing Master's words of wisdom) is provided only by the Debian package,
which installs setgid
.B games
and stores the table under
.IR /var/games/xboing/ .
Unprivileged installs (for example via Homebrew, or a build run from the
source tree) have no shared table; there
.B -scores
prints only your personal scores (it does not reference the Debian
.I /var/games
path), and the in-game global high-score screen shows an empty board. If
you achieve the top global score you are prompted for a short message
displayed under the Boing Master's name.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
Paths are resolved using the XDG Base Directory specification, with
optional overrides:
.TP
.B XBOING_LEVELS_DIR
Directory containing the level files (overrides the installed location).
.TP
.B XBOING_SOUND_DIR
Directory containing the sound files (overrides the installed location).
.TP
.B XBOING_SCORE_FILE
Path to the global high-score file (override for tests or administration).
.TP
.B XDG_DATA_HOME
Per-user data directory for personal scores and saved games
(default ~/.local/share).
.TP
.B XDG_DATA_DIRS
System data directories searched for installed levels and sounds.
.PP
The override variables take precedence over the compiled-in and XDG
locations.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I ~/.local/share/xboing/personal-scores.dat
Per-user personal high-score table ($XDG_DATA_HOME/xboing/).
.TP
.I ~/.local/share/xboing/
Saved games and other per-user data.
.TP
.I /var/games/xboing/scores.dat
Shared global high-score table (Debian package only; setgid
.BR games ).
.TP
.IR <datadir>/xboing/levels/ ", " <datadir>/xboing/sounds/
Installed level and sound data (for example
.IR /usr/share/xboing/ ", " /opt/homebrew/share/xboing/ ).
.SH NOTES
The original XBoing was written by Justin C. Kibell between 1993 and 1997
to learn Xlib, using the XPM library for pixmap graphics; version 2.4 was
released in 1996 and distributed via ftp.x.org. This package is the SDL2
modernization: the X11/Xlib graphics, audio, and event handling have been
replaced with SDL2, so the original X11-only options
.RB ( -display ", " -sync ", " -usedefcmap ", " -noicon )
no longer exist, and audio now uses SDL2 rather than the original's
machine-specific drivers.
